Right. You want a list. A monument to humanity's cyclical obsession with drawing lines in the sand and then paying other people to watch them get crossed. Here is your catalog of well-intentioned, often futile, attempts to keep the peace. Don't get your hopes up; the ending is usually just the beginning of the next chapter.

Look at him. A [Canadian peacekeeper](/Canadian_peacekeeper) back in 1976, sporting the now-iconic [UN blue helmet](/Blue_beret). A color chosen, one assumes, to be a calming, non-threatening shade of sky, which is ironic given what they're usually standing under is a hail of something less pleasant than rain.

The [United Nations](/United_Nations), in its infinite wisdom, has green-lit 71 [peacekeeping operations](/United_Nations_peacekeeping) as of April 2018. Let's be clear: this ledger of interventions doesn't even bother to include the UN's more... muscular authorizations, like the little excursions into the [Korean War](/Korean_War) and the [Gulf War](/Gulf_War). Those were different. More direct. This list is for the lingering, awkward conflicts. The 1990s, a particularly optimistic and bloody decade, saw a veritable explosion of these missions.

These operations are generally managed by the [Department of Peacekeeping Operations (DPKO)](/United_Nations_Department_of_Peacekeeping_Operations), a name that sounds both proactive and profoundly weary. They all share a few family traits: a military or police presence, a mandate, and often, an authorization to use force under the infamous [Chapter VII](/Chapter_VII_of_the_United_Nations_Charter) of the [Charter of the United Nations](/United_Nations_Charter). That's the part of the rulebook that says, "Okay, you can shoot back now."

And please, don't confuse these with "special political missions" (SPMs). Those are handled by the [Department of Political Affairs (DPA)](/United_Nations_Department_of_Political_Affairs) and are apparently different enough that they don't get to be on this list. Bureaucracy is a beautiful thing. SPMs are not included in the table below, so don't ask.

### 1940s

A hopeful, naive time. The ink on the charter was barely dry, and the world was already finding new ways to fall apart.

| Start | End | Name | Acronym | Location | Purpose | Comment |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1948 | Ongoing | [UN Truce Supervision Organization](/UNTSO) | UNTSO | [Israel](/Israel)<br>[Syria](/Syria)<br>[Lebanon](/Lebanon)<br>[Jordan](/Jordan)<br>[Egypt](/Egypt) | To send observers to watch the shaky ceasefire declared in the [Arab-Israeli conflict](/Arab%E2%80%93Israeli_conflict). A job that requires endless patience and a high tolerance for broken promises. | Authorized in the aftermath of the [First Arab-Israeli War](/1948_Arab%E2%80%93Israeli_War) in June 1948. This was the UN's very first peacekeeping mission. A precedent was set: some jobs are never, ever finished. |
| 1949 | Ongoing | [UN Military Observer Group in India and Pakistan](/UN_Military_Observer_Group_in_India_and_Pakistan) | UNMOGIP | [India](/India)<br>[Pakistan](/Pakistan) | To monitor the ceasefire line between India and [Pakistan](/Pakistan) in the perpetually contested region of [Kashmir](/Kashmir_conflict). | Kicked off after the [First Indo-Pakistani War.](/Indo-Pakistani_War_of_1947%E2%80%931948) Another mission that has become part of the landscape, a permanent fixture in a seemingly permanent dispute. |

### 1950s

The decade when they realized that just watching wasn't always going to cut it.

| Start | End | Name | Acronym | Location | Purpose | Comment |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1956 | 1967 | [UN Emergency Force I](/UNEF_I) | UNEF I | [Egypt](/Egypt) | To supervise the orderly withdrawal of Egyptian and Israeli troops after the whole world got involved in the [Suez Crisis](/Suez_Crisis). Essentially, acting as the world's most overqualified hall monitor. | This marked the debut of armed peacekeepers. The blue helmets now came with rifles. The mission ended abruptly in June 1967, right as the [Six-Day War](/Six-Day_War) was about to demonstrate how temporary peace can be. |
| 1958 | 1958 | [UN Observation Group in Lebanon](/UNOGIL) | UNOGIL | [Lebanon](/Lebanon) | To ensure troops and weapons weren't being smuggled into [Lebanon](/Lebanon) during its [1958 crisis](/1958_Lebanon_crisis). A short-lived attempt at border control. | It wrapped up by December 1958. A rare instance of a mission with a clear end date. Don't get used to it. |

### 1960s

The world got more complicated. So did the missions.

| Start | End | Name | Acronym | Location | Purpose | Comment |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1960 | 1964 | [UN Operation in the Congo](/ONUC) | ONUC | [Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville)](/Republic_of_the_Congo_(L%C3%A9opoldville)) | An ambitious attempt to prevent foreign meddling and hold the [Congo](/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo) together during the chaotic [Congo Crisis](/Congo_Crisis). | A messy, complicated affair that ended in June 1964. It became a textbook example of how quickly peacekeeping can descend into conflict. |
| 1962 | 1963 | [UN Security Force](/United_Nations_Temporary_Executive_Authority) and [UN Temporary Executive Authority](/United_Nations_Temporary_Executive_Authority) | UNSF / UNTEA | [West New Guinea](/United_Nations_Administered_West_New_Guinea) | To oversee a ceasefire and manage the transition of [Western New Guinea](/Western_New_Guinea) from [Dutch](/Netherlands_New_Guinea) colonial rule to [Indonesian](/Indonesia) administration. | A brief but significant mission that concluded in April 1963. It was one of the few times the UN directly administered a territory. |
| 1963 | 1964 | [UN Yemen Observation Mission](/UNYOM) | UNYOM | [North Yemen](/Yemen_Arab_Republic) | To supervise the disengagement of [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia) and [Egypt](/Egypt) from the simmering [North Yemeni Civil War](/North_Yemen_Civil_War). | Ended in September 1964. Another short-term observation gig. |
| 1964 | Ongoing | [UN Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus](/UNFICYP) | UNFICYP | [Cyprus](/Cyprus) | To prevent the simmering conflict between [Greek Cypriots](/Greek_Cypriots) and [Turkish Cypriots](/Turkish_Cypriots) from boiling over. It has since become a permanent part of the island's divided reality. | Still going. Peacekeepers who arrived as young soldiers have likely retired, had children, and watched those children grow up while the mission continues. |
| 1965 | 1966 | [Mission of the Representative of the Secretary-General in the Dominican Republic](/DOMREP) | DOMREP | [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic) | To observe the situation created by two rival governments in the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic) and report back. | A quiet mission that ended in October 1966. |
| 1965 | 1966 | [UN India-Pakistan Observation Mission](/UNIPOM) | UNIPOM | [India](/India)<br>[Pakistan](/Pakistan) | To supervise the ceasefire between India and Pakistan in areas outside of Kashmir following the [Second Indo-Pakistani War](/Indo-Pakistani_War_of_1965). | Wrapped up in March 1966. A companion piece to the ongoing Kashmir mission, focused on a specific conflict's aftermath. |

### 1970s

More desert, more observation, more intractable conflicts.

| Start | End | Name | Acronym | Location | Purpose | Comment |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1973 | 1979 | [UN Emergency Force II](/UNEF_II) | UNEF II | [Egypt](/Egypt) | To supervise the withdrawal of forces from the [Sinai Peninsula](/Sinai_Peninsula) after Egypt, [Syria](/Syria), and Israel had at it again in the [Yom Kippur War](/Yom_Kippur_War). | Ended in July 1979. The sequel to UNEF I, proving that some conflicts require multiple interventions. |
| 1974 | Ongoing | [UN Disengagement Observer Force](/UNDOF) | UNDOF | [Golan Heights](/Golan_Heights) (disputed between [Israel](/Israel) and [Syria](/Syria)) | To maintain the ceasefire between Syria and Israel on the strategically critical [Golan Heights](/Golan_Heights). A quiet but tense vigil. | Another "ongoing" mission. The observers have become as much a feature of the landscape as the old fortifications. |
| 1978 | Ongoing | [UN Interim Force in Lebanon](/UNIFIL) | UNIFIL | [Lebanon](/Lebanon) | Initially, to supervise Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon. Its mandate has since grown to include keeping the peace and helping the Lebanese Government assert its authority. A perpetually expanding job description. | The definition of "interim" is clearly flexible. |

### 1980s

The Cold War was thawing, but proxy wars were still hot.

| Start | End | Name | Acronym | Location | Purpose | Comment |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1988 | 1990 | [UN Good Offices Mission in Afghanistan and Pakistan](/UNGOMAP) | UNGOMAP | [Afghanistan](/Democratic_Republic_of_Afghanistan)<br>[Pakistan](/Pakistan) | To ensure [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan) and [Pakistan](/Pakistan) adhered to their agreement of mutual non-interference. A mission based on trust, which is always a gamble. | Ended in March 1990. The "good offices" closed, but the region's troubles were far from over. |
| 1988 | 1991 | [UN Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group](/UNIIMOG) | UNIIMOG | [Iraq](/Ba%27athist_Iraq)<br>[Iran](/Iran) | To supervise the ceasefire that finally ended the bloody, protracted [Iran-Iraq War](/Iran%E2%80%93Iraq_War). | Concluded in February 1991. |
| 1989 | 1991 | [UN Angola Verification Mission I](/UNAVEM_I) | UNAVEM I | [Angola](/Angola) | To verify the withdrawal of [Cuban](/Cuba) troops, who had been a major player in the long-running [Angolan Civil War](/Angolan_Civil_War). | Ended in June 1991. The first of several UN missions to Angola. It's never just one. |
| 1989 | 1990 | [UN Transition Assistance Group](/UNTAG) | UNTAG | [South West Africa](/South_West_Africa) (became [Namibia](/Namibia) after 1990) | To oversee [Namibia](/Namibia)'s first democratic elections and its transition to independence from [South Africa](/South_Africa). | A widely cited success story. It ended in March 1990 after Namibia was born. Sometimes, things actually work. |
| 1989 | 1992 | [UN Observer Group in Central America](/ONUCA) | ONUCA | [Nicaragua](/Nicaragua) | To monitor the ceasefire in the [Nicaraguan Civil War](/Nicaraguan_Revolution) and oversee the demobilization of the Contras. | Ended in January 1992. |

### 1990s

The busiest decade. The end of the Cold War didn't bring peace; it just changed the nature of the wars.

| Start | End | Name | Acronym | Location | Purpose | Comment |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1991 | 2003 | [UN Iraq-Kuwait Observation Mission](/UNIKOM) | UNIKOM | [Kuwait](/Kuwait)<br>[Iraq](/Ba%27athist_Iraq) | To enforce the newly demarcated border between [Kuwait](/Kuwait) and Iraq after the [Gulf War](/Gulf_War). Essentially, a well-armed border patrol. | Rendered obsolete and terminated in 2003 with the invasion of Iraq. |
| 1991 | 1995 | [UN Angola Verification Mission II](/UNAVEM_II) | UNAVEM II | [Angola](/Angola) | The sequel. Tasked with enforcing a new ceasefire in the still-raging Angolan Civil War. | Ended in February 1995, only to be replaced by yet another mission. |
| 1991 | 1995 | [UN Observer Mission in El Salvador](/ONUSAL) | ONUSAL | [El Salvador](/El_Salvador) | To verify compliance with peace agreements that ended the brutal [Salvadoran Civil War](/Salvadoran_Civil_War). | Wrapped up in April 1995. Another mission that saw a peace process through to its conclusion. |
| 1991 | Ongoing | [UN Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara](/MINURSO) | MINURSO | [Western Sahara](/Western_Sahara) (independence disputed by [Morocco](/Morocco)) | To implement a ceasefire and organize a referendum on the territory's future after the [Western Sahara War](/Western_Sahara_War). The referendum has yet to happen. | The ceasefire holds, mostly. The core political task remains frozen in time. |
| 1991 | 1992 | [UN Advance Mission in Cambodia](/UNAMIC) | UNAMIC | [Cambodia](/Cambodia) | A preparatory mission to pave the way for a much larger UN operation in [Cambodia](/Cambodia) following the [Cambodian–Vietnamese War](/Cambodian%E2%80%93Vietnamese_War). | Ended in March 1992, mission accomplished. It set the stage for UNTAC. |
| 1992 | 1995 | [UN Protection Force](/UN_Protection_Force) | UNPROFOR and [UNPREDEP](/UNPREDEP) | [Croatia](/Croatia)<br>[Bosnia and Herzegovina](/Bosnia_and_Herzegovina)<br>[Republic of Macedonia](/North_Macedonia) | A massive, controversial mission to protect civilians in [Croatia](/Croatia), [Bosnia and Herzegovina](/Bosnia_and_Herzegovina), and the [Republic of Macedonia](/Republic_of_Macedonia) during the catastrophic [Yugoslav Wars](/Yugoslav_Wars). | Restructured in December 1995. Its legacy is deeply complex, marked by both humanitarian successes and devastating failures to prevent atrocities like Srebrenica. |
| 1992 | 1993 | [UN Transitional Authority in Cambodia](/UNTAC) | UNTAC | [Cambodia](/United_Nations_Administered_Cambodia) | An incredibly ambitious mission to disarm factions, repatriate refugees, and organize free elections to rebuild Cambodia. | Ended in September 1993. One of the largest and most complex UN operations ever, it fundamentally reshaped a nation. |
| 1992 | 1993 | [UN Operation in Somalia I](/UNOSOM_I) | UNOSOM I | [Somalia](/Somalia) | To enforce a ceasefire during the [Somali Civil War](/Somali_Rebellion) and protect humanitarian aid delivery. It was quickly overwhelmed. | Replaced in March 1993 by UNOSOM II after being reorganized into the US-led [Unified Task Force](/Unified_Task_Force) (UNITAF). The situation was far more volatile than anticipated. |
| 1992 | 1993 | [UN Observer Mission to Verify the Referendum in Eritrea](/UN_Observer_Mission_to_Verify_the_Referendum_in_Eritrea) | UNOVER | [Ethiopia](/Transitional_Government_of_Ethiopia) | A straightforward task: monitor the referendum on [Eritrea](/Eritrea)'s independence from [Ethiopia](/Ethiopia). | Ended in April 1993. The referendum was held, the result was clear, and the mission was done. Simple. |
| 1992 | 1994 | [UN Operation in Mozambique](/ONUMOZ) | ONUMOZ | [Mozambique](/Mozambique) | To monitor the ceasefire that ended the long and devastating [Mozambican Civil War](/Mozambican_Civil_War). | Ended in December 1994, another post-conflict success story of the 90s. |
| 1993 | 1995 | [UN Operation in Somalia II](/UNOSOM_II) | UNOSOM II | [Somalia](/Somalia) | The follow-up. A more robust mission to stabilize Somalia and support humanitarian efforts. It became infamous for the Battle of Mogadishu. | Ended in March 1995. Its difficult experience deeply influenced international willingness to intervene for years to come. |
| 1993 | 1994 | [UN Observer Mission Uganda-Rwanda](/UNOMUR) | UNOMUR | [Rwanda](/Rwanda)<br>[Uganda](/Uganda) | To monitor the border and ensure the ceasefire between [Rwanda](/Rwanda) and the [rebel group](/Rwandan_Patriotic_Front) based in [Uganda](/Uganda) during the [Rwandan Civil War](/Rwandan_Civil_War) was holding. | Ended in September 1994. It was a prelude to a far greater tragedy. |
| 1993 | 2009 | [UN Observer Mission in Georgia](/UNOMIG) | UNOMIG | [Georgia](/Georgia_(country))<br>[Abkhazia](/Abkhazia) (independence from Georgia not recognized by international community) | To enforce a ceasefire between [Georgia](/Georgia_(country)) and [Abkhaz](/Abkhazia) separatists after the [Abkhaz War](/War_in_Abkhazia_(1992%E2%80%931993)). | Its mandate was not extended in June 2009 due to a Russian veto, a stark reminder that peacekeeping exists at the mercy of great power politics. |
| 1993 | 1996 | [UN Observer Mission in Liberia](/UNOMIL) | UNOMIL | [Liberia](/Liberia) | To monitor the ceasefire and elections following the brutal [First Liberian Civil War](/First_Liberian_Civil_War). | Ended in September 1997. Peace, it turned out, was temporary. |
| 1993 | 1996 | [UN Mission in Haiti](/UNMIH) | UNMIH | [Haiti](/Haiti) | To help stabilize [Haiti](/Haiti) after a [military coup](/1991_Haitian_coup_d%27%C3%A9tat) overthrew the elected government. | Ended in June 1996, the first in a long series of UN missions to Haiti. |
| 1993 | 1996 | [UN Assistance Mission for Rwanda](/UNAMIR) | UNAMIR | [Rwanda](/Rwanda) | Initially to monitor a ceasefire. Its mandate and insufficient forces left it powerless to stop the [Rwandan Genocide](/Rwandan_genocide), after which its purpose shifted to humanitarian relief. | Ended in March 1996. Its name is forever synonymous with one of the UN's darkest failures. |
| 1994 | 1994 | [UN Aouzou Strip Observer Group](/UNASOG) | UNASOG | [Chad](/Chad) | To monitor [Libya](/Libya)'s withdrawal from a disputed border territory awarded to [Chad](/Chad) by the [International Court of Justice](/International_Court_of_Justice). | A quick, successful mission that ended in June 1994. |
| 1994 | 2002 | [UN Mission of Observers in Tajikistan](/UNMOT) | UNMOT | [Tajikistan](/Tajikistan) | To monitor the ceasefire in the devastating [Tajikistani Civil War](/Tajikistani_Civil_War). | Ended in May 2000. |
| 1995 | 1997 | [UN Angola Verification Mission III](/UNAVEM_III) | UNAVEM III | [Angola](/Angola) | The trilogy continues. This time, to monitor a ceasefire and the disarmament of fighters. | Ended in June 1997, only to be succeeded by a follow-up mission, MONUA. Angola was a stubborn case. |
